Completing a large-scale computing project like identifying Lyman-break galaxies requires great attention to detail and organization. These were areas that caused issues as subtle changes often needed to take place among different files for a given fix. If a directory was not kept clean and changes were made without care, often this would lead to additional problems as the code grew. There were also issues that arose with the CHTC process time. This put a very real constraint on quality of code and as a result I put into place techniques to reduce memory and computational complexity. This often included reducing the total amount of information saved at a given point in time within operations in the hw4.R file. I also made sure that only a couple spectra were processed when testing scripts.

cB58 = readFrameFromFITS("cB58_Lyman_break.fit")

LenLam <- length(cB58$LOGLAM)

scaleX <- function(x){
  x = (x - min(x))/(max(x)-min(x))
return(x)
} 
normalize  <- function(y){
    return((y - mean(y))/sd(y))
}

cB58$LOGLAM <- scaleX(cB58$LOGLAM)
plot_spectrum <- function(spectrum_name,optimal_index){
  
  data1 = readFrameFromFITS(spectrum_name)
  I = optimal_index
  
  
  F1 <- data1$flux[I:LenLam+I]   #slice correct flux portion
  LL1 <- data1$loglam[I:LenLam+I]  #slice correct loglam portion

  LL1 = scaleX(LL1)
  F1 = normalize(F1)
  L = length(F1)

  CB_F1 <- cB58$FLUX[1:L] #slice correct flux portion
  CB_LL1 <- cB58$LOGLAM[1:L]  #slice correct loglam portion      #Note all slices should be same length

  CB <- data.frame(LogLam = LL1,Flux = c(CB_F1,F1), 
                   Spectrum = c(rep.int("Flux CB58", L),rep.int(paste("Flux",spectrum_name), L))) #bundle for ggplot 


  ggplot(CB,aes(LogLam,Flux,col=Spectrum))+geom_line()
}
plot_spectrum('spec-5287-55952-1000.fits',892)  

plot_spectrum('spec-3814-55535-1000.fits',1349)
